<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900601-0050</DOCNO><DOCID>900601-0050.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Judge Approves Sale   Of PTL TV Network   To Morris Cerullo</HL><DATE>06/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   COLUMBIA, S.C. -- A federal bankruptcy judge approved thesale of the PTL television network for $7 million to MorrisCerullo World Evangelism, a San Diego-based ministry.   Morris Cerullo's ministry, which has operations in Canada,Mexico, Brazil, Britain and the Philippines, among othersites, also has made a $45 million offer for the balance ofPTL's assets, including 2,200 acres of land, and a hotel andtheme park.</LP><TEXT>   PTL's founder, Jim Bakker, was convicted of numerousfederal fraud charges in connection with the operations.   Morris Cerullo World Evangelism said it intends to operatethe complex, known as Heritage Village Church and MissionaryFellowship Inc., as a family resort. The TV network, it said,will be run as a 24-hour-a-day, family-oriented, globalsatellite network.   Dennis Shedd, a court-appointed trustee for the PTLministry, said the bankruptcy court is expected to considerthe offer for the balance of the estate in about a month,after proper notice is given to the parties.   The sale of the network is subject to the approval of thelicense transfer by the Federal Communications Commission.The trustee said the buyer placed $7 million in escrow tocover the purchase.   A rival bidder, Oral Roberts University, had offered about$6.3 million to $6.45 million for the TV network, whichincludes production facilities and a satellite lease, Mr.Shedd said. He added that only Morris Cerullo had made anoffer for the balance of the failed religious empire.</TEXT></DOC>